@Node Introduction " -÷×÷- A/NES CGFX Introduction-÷×÷- "



        @{b}Introduction@{ub}

        It all started a day in may in the year of 1997. I was
        watching Nesticle on a PC machine and started to wonder
        why there wasn't any decent NES emulator for Amiga...
        So I (Morgan) and my friend Fredrik started this little
        project.
        We had never done anything like this before so it was
        a challenge.
        The CPU emulation (it's incredible fast) was written
        from scratch in 68020 assembly language and everything
        else concerning the emulation is also written in assembly.

        Enjoy it, and remember, if you like it and use it, 
	don't forget to support us. 



@Endnode
@Node NSF " -÷×÷- A/NES NSF-÷×÷- "

        @{b}What's an NSF file?@{ub}
	An NSF-file is music(or soundeffects) that are (usually) ripped from
	a NES-ROM. The file contains both sound-data and the replayer (similar
	to .SID files) so the playback has to be done using a 6502-emulator.

	To load an NSF, simple use the LOAD ROM button in the main window
	and pick your NSF-file (www.zophar.net/nsf/ has tons of NSF's). Then
	simply hit start.
	A small GUI will appear and tell you some information about the song.
	Use your left/right buttons to select between different songs (yes, NSF
	files can contain more than one song).
	NSF-file can even contain additional soundchannels (FDS etc.) however
	the NSF-player doesn't yet play these channels. 


        @{b}Possible problems@{ub}
	* A few NSF's that I've tried seems to have weird headers and won't 
	load properly in the NSF-player. However this seems to be quite rare
	so most NSF's should work.
	* Most NSFs are suited to be played at 60hz (NTSC) however A/NES CGFX
	doesn't yet emulate NTSC mode properly. To play back these at more
	accurate speed, try lowering the cycles/scanline settings found in
	the preferences. In most cases you can lower this to 40(!) and most
	NSFs will still function correctly. Try disabling the "limit speed"
	option aswell to for maximum CPU usage if you have problems playing
	these at correct speed.
	


@Endnode


@Node tech " -÷×÷- A/NES -÷×÷- "


        @{b}TECHNICAL INFORMATION@{ub}

        The following utilities was used during the
        development of A/NES.

                * ASM-ONE / ASM-PRO
                * GADTOOLSBOX
		* ART-PRO
		* STONECRACKER

        A/NES consists of more than 19.000 lines of 
        pure assembly code. The source code (including gui)
        is about 400 Kbyte in size.

        The 6502 cpu emulation is NOT based on any existing
        source and is written from scratch in assembly, making
        special use of the 68020 processor or better.

	The A/NES CGFX archive comes with two executables,
	ANESCGFX.020 & ANESCGFX.060. The 060 version is compiled
	for the 68060 processor, however it will run on 020/030/040
	systems aswell, but a little bit slower.
	So, if you haven't got a 060, don't use that version.

	Also, if you don't have CGFX and a graphicscard, don't
	use this version. OCS/ECS/AGA users should use the
	"normal" version found Aminet (misc/emu/anes.lha).

@Endnode

